1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Most AI agent memory systems fail in one of two ways.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:13,000
They either forget useful prior work, or preserve too much raw context and call it memory.

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Tree Ring Memory starts from a different premise: memory should age.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:31,000
Fresh work stays detailed. Older learning compresses into rings. Failures become scars. Durable truths become heartwood. Future ideas stay as seeds.

5
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:42,000
This is not a hosted memory service or a vector database wrapper. It is a framework-agnostic memory lifecycle layer for AI agents.

6
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:56,000
The current public runtime is Rust-native: CLI, SQLite and FTS storage, explainable recall, import and export, audit, consolidation, maintenance, adapters, and TUI.

7
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:12,000
Install the CLI, initialize a local memory root, store one concise project lesson, recall it by query, and record evaluated outcomes with source references.

8
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Evaluated outcomes matter because memory should not treat every claim as durable truth.

9
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:31,000
A promoted evaluation can become heartwood. A rejected experiment can become a scar, so future agents do not repeat the same failed path.

10
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:42,000
The privacy boundary matters too. Tree Ring Memory does not scrape transcripts, run a hidden recorder, or turn terminal pulses into durable memory.

11
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Durable writes are explicit: remember, evidence, import, consolidation, maintenance, TUI action, or deliberate agent action.

12
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Tree Ring Memory is in protocol-preview status. What should a portable, local-first memory layer get right before deeper framework bridges land?

13
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:02,000
Try it, break it, and leave feedback in the launch issue.
